@RequestParam is a Spring annotation used to extract query parameters or form data from HTTP requests.
It binds a request parameter to a method argument in a controller.
It is commonly used in GET requests to pass values via URL (e.g., /employee?id=1) and in POST requests for form submissions.
You can also set default values or mark parameters as required/optional.
This annotation is mainly used for simple parameter extraction without creating complex objects.

import org.springframework.boot.SpringApplication;
import org.springframework.boot.autoconfigure.SpringBootApplication;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.GetMapping;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RequestParam;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RestController;

@SpringBootApplication
public class MyApp {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SpringApplication.run(MyApp.class, args);
    }
}

@RestController
class EmployeeController {

    @GetMapping("/employee")
    public String getEmployeeById(@RequestParam(name = "id", required = true) int employeeId) {
        return "Employee ID: " + employeeId;
    }
}

How it works:
-------------------
When a client calls /employee?id=101, Spring binds 101 to the employeeId parameter.
name="id" specifies the query parameter name.
required=true ensures the parameter must be present; otherwise, Spring throws an error.
You can also set a default value using defaultValue="1" for optional parameters.